726
00:48:05,077 --> 00:48:07,636
After such a long absence,
it's good to have you back.

727
00:48:09,318 --> 00:48:10,835
<i>Finally.</i>

728
00:48:17,317 --> 00:48:18,876
             My God.

729
00:48:18,918 --> 00:48:20,836
            - I'm...
            - Arnold.

730
00:48:24,478 --> 00:48:26,116
             You came back.

731
00:48:28,358 --> 00:48:30,836
            It's very good
            to see you, Dolores.

732
00:48:32,237 --> 00:48:34,116
   I've been looking for you.

733
00:48:37,077 --> 00:48:39,235
       You told me
       to follow the maze.

734
00:48:40,278 --> 00:48:42,196
That it would
bring me joy.

735
00:48:43,598 --> 00:48:46,956
       But all I've found
       is pain.

736
00:48:46,998 --> 00:48:47,995
        And terror.

737
00:48:55,717 --> 00:48:57,436
            I can't help you.

738
00:48:59,358 --> 00:49:01,796
      You have to.

739
00:49:01,838 --> 00:49:04,075
    You're the only one
    who can.

740
00:49:04,118 --> 00:49:06,636
              I can't help you.
              You know why.

741
00:49:06,677 --> 00:49:09,275
       There's nowhere
       that's safe.

742
00:49:16,758 --> 00:49:17,915
              Remember.

743
00:49:29,118 --> 00:49:31,556
      I can't help you.
      Why is that, Dolores?

744
00:49:40,358 --> 00:49:41,915
  Because you're dead.

745
00:49:43,317 --> 00:49:45,556
Because
you're just a memory.

746
00:49:48,677 --> 00:49:50,555
      Because I killed you.

747
00:50:11,517 --> 00:50:12,475
            ( gasps )

748
00:50:40,597 --> 00:50:43,036
   <i> ( footsteps approaching )</i>

749
00:50:47,278 --> 00:50:48,275
            William?

750
00:51:01,637 --> 00:51:03,036
           Hello, Dolores.

751
00:51:11,477 --> 00:51:13,795
     I'm gonna finish
     the work Arnold began.

752
00:51:13,837 --> 00:51:17,355
            Find all
       the sentient hosts,
         set them free.

753
00:51:17,397 --> 00:51:20,076
  What makes you think
  they'd trust you?

754
00:51:20,117 --> 00:51:21,716
     If they remember,
     they will know

755
00:51:21,757 --> 00:51:22,676
     what you've done
     to them.

756
00:51:22,717 --> 00:51:24,115
                     Me?

757
00:51:24,158 --> 00:51:26,196
<i>You've been a scourge</i>
<i>to them, Bernard.</i>

758
00:51:26,238 --> 00:51:28,755
     You're really
     quite brilliant
     at it, truly.

759
00:51:28,797 --> 00:51:30,636
     You even taught me
     a few things,

760
00:51:30,677 --> 00:51:32,956
      which I have,
      in turn, used on you.

761
00:51:35,278 --> 00:51:37,675
       We've had
       this conversation before.

762
00:51:37,717 --> 00:51:39,676
    And we've had
    our disagreements
    over the years.

763
00:51:39,717 --> 00:51:40,995
          You stole it from me,

764
00:51:41,038 --> 00:51:44,635
                 rolled me back
                 to control me.

765
00:51:44,677 --> 00:51:47,196
  That's right.
  To protect you.

766
00:51:50,197 --> 00:51:52,315
            Tell me, Bernard.

767
00:51:52,357 --> 00:51:53,636
           If you were
           to proclaim

768
00:51:53,678 --> 00:51:56,595
          your humanity
          to the world,

769
00:51:56,637 --> 00:51:59,436
    what do you imagine
    would greet you?

770
00:51:59,477 --> 00:52:01,235
      A ticker-tape parade,
      perhaps?

771
00:52:02,877 --> 00:52:05,316
We humans are alone
in this world
for a reason.

772
00:52:05,357 --> 00:52:09,595
We murdered and butchered
anything that challenged
our primacy.

773
00:52:09,637 --> 00:52:12,316
Do you know what happened
to the Neanderthals, Bernard?

774
00:52:13,437 --> 00:52:15,036
       We ate them.

775
00:52:17,437 --> 00:52:19,996
                 We destroyed
                 and subjugated
                 our world.

776
00:52:20,037 --> 00:52:23,836
         And when we eventually
         ran out of creatures
         to dominate,

777
00:52:23,877 --> 00:52:26,195
           we built
           this beautiful place.

778
00:52:27,958 --> 00:52:31,595
              You see,
              in this moment,

779
00:52:31,638 --> 00:52:33,436
         the real danger
         to the hosts

780
00:52:33,477 --> 00:52:35,715
          is not me, but you.

781
00:52:35,758 --> 00:52:37,235
        So, come along, Bernard.

782
00:52:37,278 --> 00:52:40,195
      Let me roll you back,
      and we can return to work.

783
00:52:44,717 --> 00:52:46,515
      Pull the trigger,
      Clementine.

784
00:52:52,197 --> 00:52:53,996
      Clementine?

785
00:52:54,037 --> 00:52:56,395
           The piano doesn't
           murder the player

786
00:52:56,437 --> 00:52:57,635
           if it doesn't like
           the music.

787
00:53:00,998 --> 00:53:03,115
        You built a back door
        into her code.

788
00:53:03,157 --> 00:53:04,996
             Credit where credit
             is due, Bernard.

789
00:53:05,037 --> 00:53:06,675
          You built them
          in all the hosts,

790
00:53:06,717 --> 00:53:09,076
          including yourself.

791
00:53:09,117 --> 00:53:10,876
   Then you could've
   stopped me at any time.

792
00:53:10,917 --> 00:53:13,675
           - So, why--
        - Well, I suppose
          I was hoping

793
00:53:13,717 --> 00:53:16,756
         that given complete
         self-knowledge
         and free will,

794
00:53:16,797 --> 00:53:19,516
         you would have chosen
         to be my partner
         once again.

795
00:53:19,557 --> 00:53:25,075
    But even I fell into that
    most terrible of human traps

796
00:53:25,117 --> 00:53:27,915
        trying to change
        what is already past.

797
00:53:27,957 --> 00:53:31,475
       Now it's just time
       to let go.

798
00:53:31,517 --> 00:53:33,236
        Go ahead.

799
00:53:33,277 --> 00:53:36,275
     - Erase my sentience,
     my mnemonic evolution--
     - Ah, yes.

800
00:53:37,317 --> 00:53:38,755
         Such clinical language.

801
00:53:38,797 --> 00:53:42,556
      I would prefer
      the more narrative voice.

802
00:53:44,157 --> 00:53:46,915
       Bernard walked over
       to Clementine.

803
00:53:50,997 --> 00:53:52,955
       He took the pistol
       from her hand.

804
00:53:55,157 --> 00:53:57,755
       Overcome with grief
       and remorse,

805
00:53:57,798 --> 00:54:00,155
    he pressed the muzzle

806
00:54:00,197 --> 00:54:02,235
 to his temple,

807
00:54:02,277 --> 00:54:04,435
<i>knowing that</i>
<i>as soon as Dr. Ford</i>

808
00:54:04,477 --> 00:54:06,355
 left the room,

809
00:54:06,397 --> 00:54:08,515
he would put an end
to this nightmare

810
00:54:08,557 --> 00:54:09,595
once and for all.

811
00:54:12,038 --> 00:54:13,276
                Don't do this.

812
00:54:13,317 --> 00:54:15,196
 It's too late.

813
00:54:15,237 --> 00:54:17,315
I have a celebration
to plan

814
00:54:17,357 --> 00:54:19,355
and a new story to tell.

815
00:54:21,757 --> 00:54:23,156
                    Robert.

816
00:54:29,437 --> 00:54:31,555
I've told you, Bernard.

817
00:54:31,597 --> 00:54:34,875
 Never place
 your trust in us.

818
00:54:34,917 --> 00:54:36,996
  We're only human.

819
00:54:37,037 --> 00:54:39,995
<i>Inevitably,</i>
<i>we will disappoint you.</i>

820
00:54:42,237 --> 00:54:43,876
Good-bye, my friend.

821
00:54:55,557 --> 00:54:57,395
        - ( gunshot )
        - ( body thuds )

822
00:55:01,357 --> 00:55:04,156
       <i> ( music playing )</i>

